01:47.540 --> 01:49.774
Oh, my God. Oh, my God,
oh, my God, oh, my God,

01:49.776 --> 01:51.209
oh, my God!
Why the code red?

01:51.211 --> 01:53.344
I mean, if it's...
if it's about your hair,

01:53.346 --> 01:55.447
I didn't even notice;
especially not from the back.

01:55.449 --> 01:57.649
What?
Nothing.

01:57.651 --> 01:59.684
Gary Blauman is here,
and I had no idea he was coming.

01:59.686 --> 02:01.419
His reply card must've
gotten lost in the mail.

02:01.421 --> 02:02.620
I mean,
where's he gonna sit?

02:02.622 --> 02:04.923
It took us weeks to plan
the seating chart!

02:04.925 --> 02:06.891
Robin.

02:06.893 --> 02:08.158
Shh.

02:08.860 --> 02:10.961
I got you.
Huh?

02:10.964 --> 02:12.897
You're talking to
the seating chart master.

02:12.899 --> 02:15.700
At my own wedding, I managed
to sit small-town Minnesotans

02:15.702 --> 02:19.604
right next to liberal New
Yorkers with grace <i>and</i> aplomb.

02:19.606 --> 02:22.707
Table 27 still gets together
once a year for a reunion.

02:22.709 --> 02:25.176
Perhaps you've seen their photos
on Facebook.

02:27.313 --> 02:28.580
Like I said...

02:28.582 --> 02:29.981
I got you.

02:29.983 --> 02:31.182
Thanks, Marshall.

02:35.222 --> 02:37.989
Code red!

02:37.991 --> 02:39.591
Grandma's sitting
next to the band,

02:39.593 --> 02:41.926
divorced couple sitting one
table away from each other,

02:41.928 --> 02:44.028
no coherent
singles table.

02:44.030 --> 02:46.331
This is the Robin's hair
of seating charts.

02:46.333 --> 02:47.333
Singles tables are cruel.

02:47.334 --> 02:48.900
I mean, what if you went
to a wedding

02:48.902 --> 02:50.502
and there was a table
of all fat guys?

02:50.504 --> 02:52.270
That would be awesome.
You're right, it would.

02:52.272 --> 02:53.771
Let's crack this
Gary Blauman nut first,

02:53.773 --> 02:55.673
and then we'll work
on the fat guy table.

02:55.675 --> 02:57.842
Wait, did you say Gary Blauman?

02:57.844 --> 02:59.744
Yeah. Why?

02:59.746 --> 03:03.214
I... hate... that guy.

03:03.216 --> 03:04.282
Why?

03:04.284 --> 03:05.583
Remember a few years ago

03:05.585 --> 03:07.585
when I read that biography
of Teddy Roosevelt?

03:07.587 --> 03:09.187
<i>For weeks after I read it,</i>

03:09.189 --> 03:12.323
<i>I only wanted to talk</i>
<i>about one thing.</i>

03:12.325 --> 03:15.560
Teddy Roosevelt was
the coolest guy ever!

03:16.730 --> 03:18.863
Oh, that's it!
No more books, Ted.

03:18.865 --> 03:21.533
I don't like the person
you become when you read books.

03:21.535 --> 03:23.701
Here's the deal: you
get to tell us one more

03:23.703 --> 03:26.004
interesting fact
about Teddy Roosevelt.

03:26.006 --> 03:28.473
One more, and then
you're done forever.

03:28.475 --> 03:29.941
So make it a good one.

03:29.943 --> 03:32.243
Okay.

03:32.245 --> 03:34.846
He went blind in one eye...

03:34.848 --> 03:37.615
from getting hit too hard
in a boxing match...

03:38.250 --> 03:40.151
...while he was president!

03:40.153 --> 03:41.419
That's a pretty good one.
Wow.

03:41.421 --> 03:42.487
That is kind of...

03:42.489 --> 03:43.988
Right?! Oh, and when he was
at Harvard...

03:43.990 --> 03:45.890
No! No! Shut up!
Oh, my God! Please!

03:45.892 --> 03:47.992
<i>Well, one night,</i>
<i>we were throwing a party</i>

03:47.994 --> 03:50.562
<i>to celebrate... something--</i>

03:50.564 --> 03:52.096
<i>I-I can't remember what--</i>

03:52.098 --> 03:54.065
<i>when a pretty girl</i>
<i>I had never met</i>

03:54.067 --> 03:55.733
<i>noticed the book</i>
<i>on the coffee table.</i>

03:55.735 --> 03:57.702
I can't believe
you have this book.

03:57.704 --> 03:58.903
I just finished
reading it.

03:58.905 --> 04:02.473
Teddy Roosevelt was
the coolest guy ever.

04:02.475 --> 04:04.509
A unicorn.

04:04.511 --> 04:05.743
<i>I couldn't believe it.</i>

04:05.745 --> 04:07.312
It was a stroke of luck on par

04:07.314 --> 04:09.781
<i>with the 50-page manuscript</i>
<i>in Roosevelt's breast pocket</i>

04:09.783 --> 04:12.083
<i>that helped slow that</i>
<i>would-be assassin's bullet.</i>

04:12.085 --> 04:12.917
Dude, come on.

04:12.919 --> 04:14.519
Sorry. Anyway...

04:14.521 --> 04:17.088
enter Gary Blauman.

04:17.089 --> 04:19.624
Is that the Teddy
Roosevelt biography?

04:19.625 --> 04:21.426
Coolest guy ever.

04:21.428 --> 04:23.661
Right? Right?

04:23.663 --> 04:25.196
Right? Right?

04:25.198 --> 04:27.999
Right? Right?
Right?

04:28.001 --> 04:30.435
<i>So the three of us started</i>
<i>talking Teddy Roosevelt.</i>

04:30.437 --> 04:32.370
When he took that
four-minute flight

04:32.372 --> 04:33.605
on the Wright
brother's plane?

04:33.607 --> 04:34.772
So cool.

04:34.774 --> 04:36.641
The time he climbed
the tallest mountain

04:36.643 --> 04:38.443
in Europe on
his honeymoon.

04:38.445 --> 04:39.644
So cool.

04:39.646 --> 04:41.212
<i>And that's when I realized,</i>

04:41.214 --> 04:43.314
<i>Blauman and I were locked</i>
<i>in a battle of wills</i>

04:43.316 --> 04:45.516
<i>that made T.R.'s charge</i>
<i>up San Juan Hill</i>

04:45.518 --> 04:47.018
<i>look like a walk in the park.</i>

04:47.020 --> 04:49.220
<i>Or should I say,</i>
<i>in the national park,</i>

04:49.222 --> 04:50.254
<i>since it was Roosevelt</i>

04:50.256 --> 04:51.756
<i>who spearheaded</i>
<i>the establishment...</i>

04:51.758 --> 04:53.758
Dude, come on. I gave you one.

04:53.760 --> 04:56.661
The battle raged on.

04:56.663 --> 04:58.630
In a way, he was...

04:58.632 --> 05:02.700
...the archetype
of the modern politician!

05:03.603 --> 05:05.203
<i>Dude, knock it off.</i>

05:05.205 --> 05:06.938
<i>Knock what off, bro?</i>

05:06.940 --> 05:08.039
<i>This is my apartment,</i>

05:08.041 --> 05:09.140
<i>my Teddy Roosevelt</i>
<i>conversation,</i>

05:09.142 --> 05:10.508
<i>I get the girl.</i>

05:10.510 --> 05:12.977
<i>Oh, so the fact that</i>
<i>you're the incumbent means</i>

05:12.979 --> 05:14.112
<i>she should just pick you?</i>

05:14.114 --> 05:16.147
<i>Tell that</i>
<i>to William Howard Taft.</i>

05:16.149 --> 05:18.716
<i>You're calling me Taft?</i>

05:18.718 --> 05:20.518
If anyone's Taft, you're Taft!

05:20.520 --> 05:22.387
<i>I'm not Taft! I'm Teddy!</i>

05:22.389 --> 05:24.422
<i>The hell you are.</i>
<i>My name is Ted!</i>

05:24.424 --> 05:27.659
<i>Yeah, right. Go sign the</i>
<i>Payne-Aldrich Tariff Act, Taft!</i>

05:27.661 --> 05:29.927
<i>How dare you?</i>

05:29.929 --> 05:32.797
Skinny-dipping
in the Potomac River.

05:34.300 --> 05:37.001
<i>And so the standoff</i>
<i>continued, hours passed...</i>

05:37.003 --> 05:39.170
<i>then days.</i>

05:39.172 --> 05:41.472
Days passed?
Days passed.

05:41.474 --> 05:44.876
<i>Finally, a T.R. stricken</i>
<i>by tropical fever</i>

05:44.878 --> 05:48.546
<i>on his Amazon trek,</i>
<i>we could go no further.</i>

05:48.548 --> 05:51.082
When he was Assistant Secretary
of the Navy...

05:51.084 --> 05:52.650
Will you just pick
one of us already

05:52.652 --> 05:54.719
so I can either have sex
or go to sleep!

05:56.655 --> 05:58.890
Smooth, bro.

05:58.892 --> 06:01.492
After that day,
I have never liked that guy.

06:01.494 --> 06:03.628
So let's just tell Robin
this can't be done,

06:03.630 --> 06:05.263
and send Gary Blauman packing.

06:05.265 --> 06:06.731
Did you just say

06:06.733 --> 06:08.332
Gary Blauman?

06:08.334 --> 06:09.233
Yeah.

06:09.235 --> 06:11.602
I...

06:11.604 --> 06:13.371
love that guy!

06:13.373 --> 06:14.839
What?! He's the devil!

06:14.841 --> 06:16.708
He's an angel.

06:16.710 --> 06:19.811
It was 2006,
Marshall and I had broken up,

06:19.813 --> 06:21.913
and I was back in New York
feeling vulnerable

06:21.915 --> 06:24.415
and listening to
my breakup song over and over.

06:24.417 --> 06:26.718
Sugar Ray's "Fly."
You know it.

06:26.720 --> 06:28.586
Man, you know nothing
about breakups.

06:28.588 --> 06:29.954
I really don't.

06:29.956 --> 06:32.523
Anyway, then I hit bottom.

06:32.525 --> 06:33.691
There's a bottom
below Sugar Ray?

06:33.693 --> 06:35.426
Mm.

06:35.428 --> 06:37.361
What?!

06:37.363 --> 06:39.397
Why have I never
seen that before?

06:39.399 --> 06:40.565
I've been using cover-up

06:40.567 --> 06:42.900
and strategically placed straps
for a long time

06:42.902 --> 06:44.769
to keep this puppy quiet.

06:44.771 --> 06:47.038
After all the times
you guys made fun of me

06:47.040 --> 06:48.539
for my breakup butterfly
tattoo?

06:50.577 --> 06:52.877
Oh, the fact that Ted got
a butterfly tattoo,

06:52.879 --> 06:55.079
will you ever stop
being hilarious?

06:55.081 --> 06:57.081
So why is it only
half a butterfly?

06:57.083 --> 07:00.485
Because Gary Blauman saw me
in the tattoo parlor,

07:00.487 --> 07:03.121
dragged me out
and talked some sense into me.

07:03.123 --> 07:04.889
Lily, trust me,

07:04.891 --> 07:07.024
you and Marshall
are going to get back together.

07:07.026 --> 07:10.094
And when you do, you will
be so glad you did not get

07:10.096 --> 07:11.763
the other half
of that butterfly.

07:11.765 --> 07:15.933
Actually, I was gonna get a
little more than the butterfly.

07:18.570 --> 07:21.105
It's good that I ran into you.

07:21.107 --> 07:23.374
Marshall, Blauman saved you
from a lifetime

07:23.376 --> 07:26.444
of looking at Sugar Ray every
time we do it on your birthday.

07:26.446 --> 07:27.945
Find him a nice seat.

07:27.947 --> 07:30.248
No, no, do not find him a seat.

07:30.250 --> 07:32.049
I'm telling you, this guy...
You find him a nice...

07:32.051 --> 07:33.484
<i>Neither of us</i>
<i>was gonna back down,</i>

07:33.486 --> 07:35.920
so finally we decided
to take it to the groom.

07:36.890 --> 07:38.856
Wh-What's going on?
Shh!

07:38.858 --> 07:40.024
Wha...?

07:42.961 --> 07:43.961
Who's that guy?

07:43.963 --> 07:46.130
It's my ex-boyfriend.

07:49.950 --> 07:51.450
So, we're crouching
behind a van,

07:51.452 --> 07:53.052
hiding from
your ex-boyfriend.

07:53.354 --> 07:56.088
Forgive me, I'm a little bit
of a detective.

07:56.090 --> 07:57.723
It was a bad breakup?

07:57.725 --> 07:59.091
Pretty bad.

07:59.093 --> 08:01.059
Bad like
there was a big fight?

08:01.061 --> 08:03.162
Bad like there was
a big ring.

08:03.164 --> 08:05.297
Bad like this happened
in the past year?

08:05.299 --> 08:08.367
Bad like it
happened Saturday.

08:08.369 --> 08:10.335
So bad.

08:10.337 --> 08:11.603
Yeah.

08:13.873 --> 08:15.674
Okay, he's gone.

08:16.843 --> 08:19.278
I'm so sorry, Ted.

08:19.280 --> 08:21.947
I really like you,
but I'm-I'm in

08:21.949 --> 08:24.816
the weirdest place on Earth
right now.

08:24.818 --> 08:26.518
You're in a Scottish-Mexican
restaurant?

08:27.655 --> 08:28.787
Yup.

08:28.789 --> 08:31.323
Yeah, I am.

08:32.225 --> 08:34.960
It's just too soon
for me to be dating.

08:34.962 --> 08:36.895
I think I should head home.

08:36.897 --> 08:40.365
Well, want me to walk with you?

08:40.366 --> 08:43.034
Lots of scary ex-boyfriends
in this neighborhood.

08:43.037 --> 08:44.870
Sure.

08:45.805 --> 08:47.406
I do want to hear
the rest of that story.

08:47.408 --> 08:49.107
Right, right the story.

08:49.109 --> 08:50.209
Yeah.

08:50.211 --> 08:53.545
So, we decided
to take it to the groom.

08:53.547 --> 08:55.180
Did you say Gary Blauman?

08:55.182 --> 08:56.348
Yeah.

08:56.350 --> 08:57.649
Gary Blauman?

08:57.651 --> 08:58.450
Yes.

08:58.452 --> 09:01.520
Blauman... comma, Gary?

09:01.522 --> 09:03.822
Point, comma,
get to the damn.

09:03.824 --> 09:06.658
I...

09:13.433 --> 09:15.234
love...

09:15.236 --> 09:17.402
that we have the opportunity
to destroy

09:17.404 --> 09:20.539
Gary Blauman's weekend by
kicking him out of the wedding!

09:20.541 --> 09:23.909
Yes! Gary Blauman Haters' Club
right here!

09:23.911 --> 09:25.744
What that guy did to me.

09:25.746 --> 09:28.347
Oh... God!

09:28.349 --> 09:29.414
It makes me

09:29.416 --> 09:31.583
furious to this day!

09:31.585 --> 09:34.019
Okay, okay, I'm gonna try
and tell this story

09:34.021 --> 09:35.621
without completely losing it.

09:35.623 --> 09:37.689
Ready? Okay, here goes.

09:37.691 --> 09:39.224
I was at the...

09:42.462 --> 09:44.029
Nope, not gonna happen.
Give me a second.

09:44.031 --> 09:45.597
Ooh!
Ooh!

09:45.599 --> 09:47.299
I was at the bar.

09:47.301 --> 09:49.167
Hey, Barney!

09:49.169 --> 09:50.502
What's up, Blauman?
Have a seat.

09:50.504 --> 09:51.737
Oh, thanks.

09:51.739 --> 09:54.239
Your fries.
Need anything?

09:54.241 --> 09:55.941
I'm good, thanks.

09:55.943 --> 09:58.810
Oh, but he was not good, thanks.

09:58.812 --> 10:01.079
He was not good, thanks, at all!

10:01.081 --> 10:04.116
Oh, what? Did he take
one of your fries?

10:04.118 --> 10:05.817
Take one?

10:06.753 --> 10:08.420
Take one?

10:08.422 --> 10:10.188
Lily, it would have been
one thing

10:10.190 --> 10:13.158
if he took one of my fries;
that would have been one thing.

10:13.160 --> 10:15.861
No, Lily, that day,

10:15.863 --> 10:18.030
Blauman took...

10:21.467 --> 10:23.935
...four of my fries!

10:23.937 --> 10:26.271
But that's not even the capper!

10:26.273 --> 10:28.774
<i>Here's the part that still</i>
<i>keeps me up at night:</i>

10:28.776 --> 10:30.709
<i>the fourth fry he took...</i>

10:30.711 --> 10:33.245
the fourth fry he took...

10:36.116 --> 10:37.816
Buddy, you oka... you okay?

10:40.487 --> 10:43.088
The fourth fry he took...

10:45.491 --> 10:47.759
